{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489614"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:23:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:23:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"702"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"702","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/702"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.27,0.56,0.14,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"702"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102060"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"702","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/702"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"702"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84514"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"432"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"3505"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1057"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1160"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32876"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34771"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42131"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43969"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102060","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102060"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 63-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a four-month history of deteriorating vision. He has a 15-year history of type II diabetes mellitus, managed with metformin and empagliflozin. He takes no other regular medications. He has a 30 pack-year smoking history and drinks four standard drinks a day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears overweight with a BMI of 35 kg/m\u00b2. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 145/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO\u2082 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. The rest of the physical examination is normal. Fundoscopy is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for his visual changes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Central retinal artery occlusion","Age-related macular degeneration","Diabetic retinopathy","Hypertensive retinopathy","Tobacco-related optic neuropathy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe fundus image shows evidence of dot-blot haemorrhages and hard exudates (yellow lipid lesions with relatively well-defined borders, often arranged in a ring). These changes are consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Ediabetic retinopathy\u003C/strong\u003E. This is a common microvascular complication of diabetes mellitus, particularly in patients with long-standing disease. The patient\u0027s 15-year history of diabetes puts him at significant risk for this complication. Management should focus on optimising glycaemic control with his current medications and addressing his multiple cardiovascular risk factors including smoking, alcohol consumption, and borderline elevated blood pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertensive retinopathy\u003C/strong\u003E may also present with dot-blot haemorrhages and hard exudates; however, arteriolar narrowing, arteriovenous nipping, and flame-shaped haemorrhages are more characteristic. While the patient\u0027s blood pressure is borderline elevated at 145/85 mmHg, the retinal findings are more consistent with diabetic changes, especially given his long history of diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECentral retinal artery occlusion\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with acute, sudden vision loss and a pale retina with a \u0027cherry red\u0027 spot at the macula. This is an ocular emergency with a different presentation than the gradual visual deterioration described in this case. The fundoscopic findings also do not match this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAge-related macular degeneration\u003C/strong\u003E may present with drusen (yellow fatty deposits) which can be confused with the hard exudates of diabetic retinopathy. However, hard exudates usually occur in association with haemorrhages and microaneurysms in a ring pattern surrounding the macula, as seen in this case. Drusen are typically more widespread throughout the retina and have a different appearance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETobacco-related optic neuropathy\u003C/strong\u003E (formerly called tobacco amblyopia) is a form of nutritional optic neuropathy presenting with swelling and pallor of the optic nerve head. While the patient has a significant smoking history, the fundoscopic findings do not show optic nerve changes but rather retinal vascular pathology consistent with diabetic retinopathy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dot-blot haemorrhages and hard exudates are consistent with diabetic retinopathy.","Diabetic retinopathy is a common microvascular complication of diabetes mellitus that can lead to vision loss.","Optimal glycaemic control and management of cardiovascular risk factors are essential in preventing progression of diabetic retinopathy."],"references":["Bowling, Brad. 2015. Kanski\u2019s Clinical Ophthalmology. 8th ed. London, England: W B Saunders.","Wang W, Lo ACY. Diabetic Retinopathy: Pathophysiology and Treatments. Int J Mol Sci. 2018 Jun 20;19(6):1816. doi: 10.3390/ijms19061816. PMID: 29925789; PMCID: PMC6032159. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29925789/","Shukla UV, Tripathy K. Diabetic Retinopathy. 2023 Aug 25. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32809640."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84514"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"702"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18471"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18471"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3ed3a75e-b389-4908-a703-dd566ccbbda4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3ed3a75e-b389-4908-a703-dd566ccbbda4.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":382,"height":287}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84514","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84514"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-07T14:09:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-07T14:09:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"702"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102060"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"att